# Per-paper directives example for explainer-batch.
#
# To use: copy this file next to a PDF in input/ and rename it to match the
# PDF's basename. For input/my-paper.pdf the sidecar is input/my-paper.focus.md.
#
# All directives are optional. Lines beginning with `#` are treated as part of
# the free-text focus block (no special comment syntax); delete or replace the
# block at the bottom of this file when you adapt it.
#
# Structured directives (parsed line-by-line, stripped before the model sees
# the prose). Unknown or malformed directive lines are ignored silently.

# Force a specific figure as the lead image. Accepts "Figure 3", "Fig 3.2",
# "fig. 4a", etc. Normalised to "Figure N" internally.
image: Figure 3

# Optional caption override for the lead image. Free text.
image_caption: Source (2026), Figure 3. Annual spend by firm type.

# Optional alt text for the lead image. Free text.
image_alt: Bar chart comparing spend brackets across four firm sizes.

# Optional 1-based page hint. When set, the figure cropper uses this page
# directly instead of searching for the caption. Useful when the caption-text
# match is ambiguous or the figure appears across page boundaries.
image_page_hint: 5

# Everything below the last structured directive becomes the free-text focus
# block. It is appended verbatim to the user message under the heading
# "READER EMPHASIS FOR THIS PAPER" — write it as you would tell a colleague
# which angle to take.

Frame this for an infrastructure-leadership reader, not an ML researcher.
Lead with the deployment cost trade-off rather than the accuracy delta.
Skip the related-work survey; we have read it.
